{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20140728040554|618763967","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"James_Langevin","to":"James Langevin"}],"pages":{"597070":{"pageid":597070,"ns":0,"title":"James Langevin","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-08-18T20:19:46Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox Congressman\n| name = Jim Langevin\n| image name = James R. Langevin 113th Congress.jpg\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1964|04|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Providence, Rhode Island]]\n| state = [[Rhode Island]]\n| district = [[Rhode Island's 2nd congressional district|2nd]]\n| term_start = January 3, 2001\n| preceded = [[Bob Weygand]]\n| succeeded = Incumbent\n|order1=[[Secretary of State of Rhode Island]]\n|term_start1= January 1995\n|term_end1=January 2001\n|preceded1=Barbara Leonard\n|succeeded1=Ed Inman\n|state_house2 = Rhode Island\n|district2=29th\n|term_start2= January 1989\n|term_end2=January 1995\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n| spouse = None\n| religion = [[Roman Catholic]]ism\n| occupation= [[Politician]]\n| alma_mater= [[Rhode Island College]]<br>[[Harvard University]] <small>([[Master of Public Administration|M.P.A.]])</small>\n| residence= [[Warwick, Rhode Island]]\n}}\n\n'''James R. Langevin''' (born April 22, 1964) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|RI|2}}, serving since 2001. He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nLangevin was born in [[Providence, Rhode Island]]. He attended [[Bishop Hendricken High School]], located in [[Warwick, Rhode Island]], and then went on to study at [[Rhode Island College]], from which he received an undergraduate degree, in addition to serving as President of Student Community Government, Inc., and he has a [[Masters of Public Administration]] from the [[Kennedy School of Government]] of [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite web | title=U.S. Representative Jim Langevin at house.gov | url=http://langevin.house.gov/about.shtml | accessdate=2008-04-22 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080327013901/http://langevin.house.gov/about.shtml <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-03-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, at age 16, he was seriously injured in an accidental shooting. He had been working as a volunteer at the Warwick Police Department when a weapon accidentally discharged, leaving him a [[quadriplegic]].\n\n==Rhode Island government==\nLangevin's first experience in politics was when he was elected to the state's 1986 [[Constitutional convention (political meeting)|constitutional convention]] and was named its secretary. Langevin, who uses a wheelchair, once ran on the slogan \"I'll stand up for you\", which he stated during a meeting in West Warwick.\n\nLangevin was first elected a member of the [[Rhode Island General Assembly]] in 1988 and served as a state representative until 1994. He was elected [[Secretary of State of Rhode Island]] in November 1994, defeating Republican incumbent [[Barbara Leonard]]. While Secretary of State, he earned a reputation for weeding out corruption in state government.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Strategic Forces|Subcommittee on Strategic Forces]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities|Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities]] (Ranking Member)\n*'''[[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence]]'''\n\n===Caucus Memberships===\n*Congressional Arts Caucus\n\n==Political positions==\n===Abortion===\nLangevin has a mixed record on abortion. He has voted both to restrict and defend the choice to have the procedure. He voted against [http://www.ontheissues.org/House/James_Langevin_Abortion.htm banning abortion coverage] in the Affordable Care Act, however he has voted for the Abortion Pain Bill, which seeks \u201cto ensure that women seeking an abortion are fully informed regarding the pain experienced by their unborn child.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=11772&can_id=55787 |title=Project Vote Smart - Representative Langevin on HR 6099 - Abortion Pain Bill |publisher=Votesmart.org |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> However, he strongly promotes contraceptive availability, and in a statement in 2007 said, \u201cI have great respect for the passion displayed by [[Chris Smith (New Jersey politician)|Mr. Smith]] and [[Bart Stupak|Mr. Stupak]] and I share their opposition to abortion. However, in this instance I must strongly disagree with their decision to prevent the distribution of contraception to some of the most poor and needy people and nations in the world.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/speech_detail.php?sc_id=296703 |title=Project Vote Smart - Representative James R. 'Jim' Langevin - The Department Of State, Foreigh Operations And Related Programs Appropriations Act, 2008-Continued |publisher=Votesmart.org |date=2007-06-21 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> Because of his mixed stance on the issue, he has received fluctuating ratings from interest groups such as Planned Parenthood and the National Right to Life Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=55787 |title=Project Vote Smart - Representative James R. 'Jim' Langevin - Interest Group Ratings |publisher=Votesmart.org |date=2010-05-14 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref>\n\nLangevin believes that [[abortion]] should be legal when the pregnancy is a result of incest or rape or when the pregnancy endangers the life of the mother, but does wish to decrease the number of abortions in the country.<ref name=\"votesmart2000\">{{cite web | title=Congressional Election 2000 National Political Awareness Test | url=http://www.votesmart.org/npat.php?can_id=55787}}</ref>  His relatively complex stance on abortion contributes to somewhat contradictory interest group ratings because of his supporting of various bills: Representative Langevin\u2019s stance on abortion supported the interests of the NARAL Pro-Choice America 0 percent in 2006 but in 2007, the same group gave Representative Langevin a grade of 100 and the National Right to Life Committee gave the Representative zero points, with points assigned for actions connected to a pro-life anti-abortion agenda.<ref name=\"votesmart3\">{{cite web | title=Project Vote Smart Interest Group Ratings of James Langevin | url=http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=55787}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\nOn the issue of Health Care, Langevin has strongly demonstrated his support of reform. In May 2009, he introduced the American Health Benefits Program Act of 2009, which has the stated purpose of \"amending the Social Security Act and the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 to assure comprehensive, affordable health insurance coverage for all Americans through an American Health Benefits Program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h111-2399 |title=H.R. 2399: American Health Benefits Program Act of 2009 |publisher=GovTrack.us |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> He has voted in favor of health care extensively during his time in office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/voting_category.php?can_id=55787&type=category&category=38&go.x=19&go.y=8 |title=Project Vote Smart - Representative James R. 'Jim' Langevin - Voting Record |publisher=Votesmart.org |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> In addition, he receives much of his campaign donations from health professionals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00009724&cycle=2008 |title=Jim Langevin: Campaign Finance/Money - Summary - Congressman 2008 |publisher=OpenSecrets |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> Langevin stated his goal for universal health care as \u201ca system of portable and continuous coverage based on quality, affordability and choice that promotes investment in long-term prevention and drives down the cost of care over time.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimlangevin.com/issues/health_care.html |title=Jim Langevin for Congress: Issues: Health Care |publisher=Jimlangevin.com |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n===Labor===\nLangevin is considered strongly pro-labor. He has received $130,000 in campaign contributions from pro-labor groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://63.e5bed1.client.atlantech.net/politicians/industries.php?cycle=2008&cid=N00009724&type=I |title=Jim Langevin: Campaign Finance/Money - Industries - Congressman 2008 &#124; OpenSecrets |publisher=63.e5bed1.client.atlantech.net |date=2009-07-13 |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> During his time in office, he has supported labor interests in over 25 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/voting_category.php?can_id=55787&type=category&category=43&go.x=5&go.y=13 |title=Project Vote Smart - Representative James R. 'Jim' Langevin - Voting Record |publisher=Votesmart.org |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> Numerous labor interest groups have rated him extremely highly, including the United Auto Workers, the AFL-CIO, and the Utility Workers Union of America.<ref name=\"votesmart1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_category.php?category=43&go.x=11&go.y=11&can_id=55787&type=category |title=Project Vote Smart - Representative James R. 'Jim' Langevin - Interest Group Ratings |publisher=Votesmart.org |date= |accessdate=2010-07-12}}</ref> Interestingly, however, the Latin America Working Group and The Alliance for Worker Freedom have ranked Langevin very poorly.<ref name=\"votesmart1\"/>\n\n===Gun control===\nHe supports [[gun control]], and co-sponsored a 2005 bill which would have reauthorized the 1994 [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban|assault weapons ban]], which had expired in 2004.\n\n===Stem cell research===\nOne of Langevin\u2019s top priorities as a Member of Congress has been the expansion of federal funding of embryonic stem cell research.<ref name=\"jimlangevin1\">{{cite web | title=James Langevin for Congress: Stem Cells | url=http://www.jimlangevin.com/issues/stem_cell_research.html}}</ref> His policy position is driven by his paralysis and the possibilities that stem cell research provide in helping this condition; he joined other members of the House in introducing the Stem Cell Research Enhancement Act of 2005, expanding the limited funding put in place in 2001.<ref name=\"jimlangevin1\"/>\n\n===Cybersecurity===\nLangevin helped to found the House Cybersecurity Caucus, which he co-chairs.<ref name=Carney>Carney, Timothy (2011-04-27) [http://washingtonexaminer.com/politics/2011/04/rise-cybersecurity-industrial-complex The rise of the cybersecurity-industrial complex], ''[[Washington Examiner]]''</ref> The Representative has appeared on ''60 Minutes'' speaking about the national security challenges the country will face this century in regards to protecting infrastructure and data.<ref>\"Cyber security is the topic for Langevin on ''60 Minutes''\", Providence Journal-Bulletin, November 8, 2009</ref> Langevin has said that he hopes to raise awareness of the need for security in that area and supports strict penalties for internet crimes as well as strong internet privacy laws.<ref name=\"votesmart2000\"/>\n\nRep. Langevin supports cybersecurity measures as long as they do not add \"unnecessary regulations to business\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://votesmart.org/public-statement/754506/langevin-responds-to-panettas-stark-warnings-about-cyber-threats#.UK05beS5PTo |title=Langevin Responds to Panetta's Stark Warnings about Cyber Threats |publisher=Project Vote Smart |accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> His state of Rhode Island passed a statewide cybersecurity plan which Langevin greatly supported in October 2012. In May of 2012, Langevin proposed an amendment to the National Defense Authorization Act(NDAA) which would account for the cyber risks that United States faces in terms of national security, saying without these measures the United States is \" ignoring key aspects of what is fast becoming the biggest threat to our security\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/694758/langevin-proposes-cybersecurity-amendments-to-defense-bill/?search=cyber#.UK06V-S5PTo |title=Langevin Proposes Cybersecurity Amendments to Defense Bill |publisher=Project Vote Smart |accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"Cybersecurity contractors [[General Dynamics]] and [[Raytheon]] were Langevin's two top sources for campaign contributions\" in the 2010 election.<ref name=Carney/>\n\n===Armed forces===\nLangevin, who serves on the Committee of Armed Services, has regularly voted for additional support of armed forces in Iraq and Afghanistan but he has voted for a timeline for U.S. forces to leave Iraq as well as a ban on any permanent U.S. bases in the country.<ref>{{cite web | title=James Langevin's Voting Record on Defense | url=http://www.votesmart.org/voting_category.php?can_id=55787&category=22}}</ref> Langevin has also voted against limiting the interrogation techniques used in fighting terror and the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web | title=James Langevin's Voting Record on the Military | url=http://www.votesmart.org/voting_category.php?can_id=55787&type=category&category=47&go.x=14&go.y=11}}</ref>\n\n===Tax cuts===\nLangevin, who serves on the Congressional Committee on the Budget, believes in tax-cuts for low-income and middle class citizens while eliminating the tax cuts made for the wealthy, indicating in his Political Courage Test that he wishes to \u201cgreatly decrease\u201d taxes for families making less than $75,000.<ref name=\"votesmart2000\"/>  Langevin also supports temporary incentives for businesses to invest in job creation. Representative Langevin, with a 100% rating from the AFL-CIO, is pro-labor and supports the regulation of business.<ref name=\"votesmart3\"/>\n\n===Advocacy for people with disabilities===\nLangevin is known as an advocate for people with disabilities and for [[universal health care]], being himself a [[quadriplegia|quadriplegic]]. He is the first quadriplegic to serve in Congress.<ref>http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2010/07/historic-lift-wheelchairbound-member-presides-over-house/</ref>\n\nOn July 27, 2004, he spoke to the [[Democratic National Convention]], largely on the subject of stem cell research.\n\nIn March 2007, Langevin became a co-sponsor of the [[Christopher Reeve|Christopher]] and [[Dana Reeve|Dana]] [[Christopher and Dana Reeve Foundation|Reeve]] Paralysis Act, which had the stated purpose of \"enhancing and furthering research into paralysis and to improve rehabilitation and the quality of life for persons living with paralysis and other physical disabilities.\" The bill passed the House of Representatives but not the [[United States Senate|Senate]]. However, in 2009, the bill was included in the [[Omnibus Public Land Management Act]], also co-sponsored by Langevin, which passed both houses of Congress and was signed into law by President [[Barack Obama]].\n\nFor the Presidency in 2008, Langevin announced his support for Sen. [[Hillary Clinton]] (D-NY),<ref>{{cite news | title=Rhode Island Rep. Jim Langevin Endorses Clinton | date=June 1, 2007 | url=http://www.hillaryclinton.com/news/release/view/?id=1884 | accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref> by serving as a special adviser on issues ranging from stem cell research to people with disabilities.\n\nOn July 26th, 2010, Langevin became the first member of Congress to preside over the House of Representatives while using a wheelchair.<ref>http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2010/07/historic-lift-wheelchairbound-member-presides-over-house/</ref> The House had just recently installed a wheelchair lift leading up to the Speaker\u2019s rostrum.<ref>http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2010/07/historic-lift-wheelchairbound-member-presides-over-house/</ref>\n\n===The Environment===\nRepresentative Langevin leans to the left on environmental and energy issues in Congress. Environmental issue groups have generally given him high ratings; more recently he received a 97% from the League of Conservation Voters in 2011. He has also received a rating of 100% from the Defenders of Wildlife Foundation. Conservative issue groups concerning the energy and the environment have given him very low ratings. He is a strong supporter of alternative energy from oil and coal, voting 'Nay' for the Stop the War Against Coal Act of September 2012<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/bill/15821/stop-the-war-on-coal-act-of-2012#.UK0z_OS5PTo |title=HR 3409 - Stop the War on Coal Act of 2012 - Key Vote |publisher=Project Vote Smart |accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> and he has supported measures for new wind farms in New England. He has praised these developments, saying wind farm \"development holds great promise for Rhode Island and the country to have more stable and cleaner energy resources, while boosting our economy by presenting an opportunity to build a manufacturing base for these turbines and create quality jobs in the Ocean State.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/721289/langevin-applauds-key-step-toward-ri-wind-farm#.UK008-S5PTo |title=Langevin Applauds Key Step Toward RI Wind Farm |publisher=Project Vote Smart |accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/633649/interior-launches-leasing-process-for-commercial-wind-energy-offshore-rhode-island-and-massachusetts#.UK01F-S5PTo |title=Interior Launches Leasing Process for Commercial Wind Energy Offshore Rhode Island and Massachusetts |publisher=Project Vote Smart |accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Langevin strongly opposed the Energy Tax Prevention Act, which would limit the EPA's ability to regulate carbon outputs. Calling the act the \"Dirty Air Act,\" Langevin explained that in passing this act America would be \"turning back the progress we have made to protect our health under the Clean Air Act,\" also claiming that the passage of the bill would be \"continuing our nation's addiction to foreign oil.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/601413/energy-tax-prevention-act-of-2011#.UK00-uS5PTo |title=\nEnergy Tax Prevention Act of 2011 |publisher=Project Vote Smart |accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref> Moreover, he has fought for more environmental regulations that he believes will help Rhode Islanders live healthier lives, saying that \"protecting the environment is a matter of pride.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/83109/langevin-kennedy-urge-defeat-of-anti-environmental-legislation#.UK01E-S5PTo |title=Langevin, Kennedy Urge Defeat of Anti-Environmental Legislation |publisher=Project Vote Smart |accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Political campaigns==\nLangevin was first elected to the [[United States House of Representatives]] in 2000, defeating perennial candidate [[Robert Tingle]] for a seat that was left open when Congressman [[Robert Weygand]] ran for the U.S. Senate. He took office in 2001, representing [[Rhode Island's 2nd congressional district]]. He has been re-elected with relative ease ever since, defeating independent Rodney Driver in 2006 and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Mark Zaccaria in 2008.\n\n;2010\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Rhode Island, 2010#District 2}}\nIn 2010, he again defeated Republican nominee Mark Zaccaria.\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Rhode Island, 2012#District 2}}\nLangevin ran for reelection in the 2nd District.<ref name=\"Go Local\">{{cite web|url=http://www.golocalprov.com/politics/jim-langevin/|title=Langevin's Influence Jeopardized in Minority|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=April 7, 2012|work=GoLocalProv|first=Steve|last=Peoples}}</ref> He was challenged by Republican nominee Michael Riley and Independent Abel Collins, an environmental activist.<ref name=\"Environmentalist District 2\">{{cite news|last=Arditi|first=Lynn|title=Environmental activist challenges Langevin for District 2 seat|url=http://news.providencejournal.com/breaking-news/2012/06/environmental-a-1.html|accessdate=16 June 2012|newspaper=The Providence Journal|date=7 June 2012}}</ref> Langevin was re-elected with 55.7% of the vote.<ref name=\"RI 2012 House race\">{{cite web|title=2012 House Races|url=http://www.politico.com/2012-election/map/#/House/2012/RI|publisher=Politico|accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://langevin.house.gov/ Congressman Jim Langevin] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.jimlangevin.com/ Jim Langevin for Congress] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Rhode_Island/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/James_Langevin_%5BD-2%5D|Jim Langevin}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = l000559 | ballot = Jim_Langevin | nndb = 518/000039401 | votesmart = 55787 | govtrack = 400230 | opencong = 400230 | rollcall = 7428 | politifact = james-langevin | fec = H0RI02139 | opensecrets 